<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06052l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06052l">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06052l"> 52(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> riddles / charades / draughts / chess</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Est-il besoin de rappeler que certains jeux, d&apos;ailleurs pleins d&apos;attrait pour nombre d&apos;enfants, sont propres entre tous &agrave; aiguiser l&apos;esprit, &agrave; exercer sa sagacit&eacute;, ses facult&eacute;s d&apos;attention et d&apos;invention (1), savoir: les <mark>Charades</mark>, les Charades en action, les <mark>Devinettes</mark> et les &Eacute;nigmes (2), les Dominos, <mark>les Dames</mark>, les &Eacute;checs</mark>. <font color="green">[Is it necessary to recall that certain games, besides full of attraction for a number of children, are fit among all to sharpen the mind, to exercise its sagacity, its faculties of attention and invention (1), namely: Charades, Charades in action, Riddles and Enigmas (2), Dominos, Draughts, Chess.]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 107-8</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
